In the United States, 21 percent of known species are threatened or extinct . California has more threatened amphibians than any other state, according to Conservation International, accounting for 13 of the nation's 54 . Many are in the higher elevations of the Sierra Nevada, including Yosemite National Park.
 The severity of the global threat to thousands of species of frogs, salamanders and other amphibians makes them perhaps the most endangered class of animals on Earth, with their rapid decline outpacing that of mammals and birds.